From: Blakestream-GaintB <sid@blakestream.local>
Subject: [PATCH 5/5] driver-baikalu: skip baikal_send_work auto-refill for disabled miners

Found while validating the 2-boards-idle case in production:

  With patches 1+2+4 applied, ascdisable correctly idles a board from
  sgminer's per-thread perspective: Enabled=N, MHS 5s=0, sgminer's
  per-thread Total MH counter freezes (the thread is suspended).

  BUT — looking at the device-level behaviour over time, the *firmware
  side* of the disabled board kept hashing forever. Symptom: the
  disabled board's Accepted counter slowly incremented and the pool
  showed shares being submitted on its behalf, even though sgminer's
  Total MH was frozen.

Root cause: baikal_process_result() has a SECOND work-push path that
patch 1 doesn't cover. When the firmware sets the 0x02 bit on a
result message ("I need more work"), the function unconditionally
calls baikal_send_work(baikal, i) to refill that miner's queue:

  if (msg.param & 0x02) {
      baikal_send_work(baikal, i);
  }

This auto-refill ignores cgpu->deven completely. The result is a
self-sustaining loop:

  1. Disabled miner's FIFO has work in it at the moment of disable
  2. Firmware hashes it, finds nonces, returns them via the result poll
  3. Result message also signals "queue is getting low, send more"
  4. baikal_process_result calls baikal_send_work for the disabled miner
  5. Firmware FIFO refills, miner keeps hashing
  6. Loop forever

Fix: gate the auto-refill on cgpu->deven, mirroring patch 1's check
in baikal_update_work. With this gate, the firmware never gets new
work after a disable, the FIFO drains in ~7 seconds (one queue worth),
and then the board sits truly idle.

Validation on the live device after patch 5: configured boards 0+1
to idle, board 2 to mining. Sampled devs API at T+0 and T+60:

  ASC0 (idle):  Total MH=420741 → 420741 (frozen, +0)
                Accepted=0 → 0 (frozen)
                Last Valid Work=startup time (frozen)
  ASC1 (idle):  Total MH=422031 → 422031 (frozen, +0)
                Accepted=1 → 1 (frozen, the lone FIFO drain share)
                Last Valid Work=startup time (frozen)
  ASC2 (mine):  Total MH=7.7TH → 12.2TH (+4.5TH = 74 GH/s × 60s)
                Accepted=2 → 3
                Last Valid Work=updates every poll cycle

Both disabled boards are now genuinely silent at the firmware level,
not just at the sgminer-accounting level. The Accepted=1 on each
disabled board is the FIFO drain — the ~7 seconds of work that was
already queued at startup before the disable command went through.
After that, zero hashing.
---
 driver-baikalu.c | 12 +++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/driver-baikalu.c b/driver-baikalu.c
--- a/driver-baikalu.c
+++ b/driver-baikalu.c
@@ -768,9 +768,19 @@ static bool baikal_process_result(struct cgpu_info *baikal)
                 baikal_checknonce(baikal, &msg);
             }

-            if (msg.param & 0x02) {
-                baikal_send_work(baikal, i);
-            }
+            if (msg.param & 0x02) {
+                /* PATCH 5: skip auto-refill for administratively disabled
+                 * miners. Patch 1 only covered baikal_update_work; this is
+                 * the OTHER work-push path. Without this skip, the firmware
+                 * keeps requesting more work via the result-poll bit and
+                 * the disabled board hashes forever. With this skip the
+                 * FIFO drains naturally and the board goes truly idle. */
+                {
+                    struct thr_info *_t = mining_thr[miner->thr_id];
+                    if (!_t || !_t->cgpu || _t->cgpu->deven != DEV_DISABLED) {
+                        baikal_send_work(baikal, i);
+                    }
+                }
+            }

             if (msg.param & 0x04) {
                 return false;
